					Product Measures &nbsp;
					Given two&nbsp;measurable&nbsp;spaces&nbsp;E&nbsp;and&nbsp;F&nbsp;and&nbsp;two measures&nbsp;μ&nbsp;and&nbsp;ν&nbsp;deﬁned&nbsp;on&nbsp;E &nbsp;
					and&nbsp;F&nbsp;respectively,&nbsp;one&nbsp;can&nbsp;construct&nbsp;a&nbsp;measure&nbsp;on&nbsp;the Cartesian&nbsp;product&nbsp;E&nbsp;×&nbsp;F &nbsp;
					equipped with the product σ-ﬁeld. This measure is called the product measure of μ &nbsp;
					and&nbsp;ν&nbsp;and&nbsp;denoted&nbsp;by&nbsp;μ&nbsp;⊗&nbsp;ν.&nbsp;The&nbsp;integral&nbsp;of&nbsp;a&nbsp;real&nbsp;function&nbsp;f&nbsp;(x,&nbsp;y)&nbsp;with&nbsp;respect&nbsp;to &nbsp;
					μ&nbsp;⊗&nbsp;ν&nbsp;can&nbsp;be&nbsp;evaluated&nbsp;by&nbsp;computing&nbsp;ﬁrst&nbsp;the&nbsp;integral&nbsp;of&nbsp;the&nbsp;function&nbsp;x&nbsp;ꢇ→&nbsp;f (x, y) &nbsp;
					with respect to&nbsp;the&nbsp;measure&nbsp;μ(dx)&nbsp;and&nbsp;then integrating&nbsp;the&nbsp;value&nbsp;of&nbsp;this&nbsp;integral &nbsp;
					with respect to ν(dy), or conversely. This is the famous Fubini theorem, which holds &nbsp;
					under appropriate&nbsp;conditions&nbsp;on&nbsp;the&nbsp;function&nbsp;f&nbsp;,&nbsp;and&nbsp;in&nbsp;particular&nbsp;if&nbsp;f&nbsp;is&nbsp;nonnegative &nbsp;
					and measurable. Beyond its important applications in analysis (integration by parts, &nbsp;
					convolution, etc.)&nbsp;or&nbsp;in probability&nbsp;theory,&nbsp;the&nbsp;Fubini&nbsp;theorem is&nbsp;also an&nbsp;essential &nbsp;
					tool for&nbsp;the&nbsp;effective&nbsp;calculation&nbsp;of&nbsp;integrals.&nbsp;As&nbsp;a&nbsp;typical&nbsp;application,&nbsp;we&nbsp;compute &nbsp;
					d
					the volume&nbsp;of&nbsp;the&nbsp;unit&nbsp;ball&nbsp;in&nbsp;R&nbsp;. &nbsp;
