					construction of&nbsp;product&nbsp;measures&nbsp;in&nbsp;Chapter 5 to the case of inﬁnite&nbsp;products, &nbsp;
					see for instance Chapter 8 in [7]. More&nbsp;generally, the&nbsp;Kolmogorov&nbsp;extension &nbsp;
					theorem (see, in&nbsp;particular,&nbsp;Chapter 7&nbsp;of&nbsp;Billingsley [1]) allows one to&nbsp;construct &nbsp;
					random processes with&nbsp;prescribed ﬁnite-dimensional&nbsp;marginals, and&nbsp;this&nbsp;applies &nbsp;
					to independent&nbsp;sequences&nbsp;as&nbsp;a very&nbsp;special&nbsp;case. A more&nbsp;elegant approach&nbsp;to&nbsp;the &nbsp;
					Poisson process calculations in Section 9.7 can be given via the concept of Poisson &nbsp;
					measures, see Kingman&nbsp;[11]. &nbsp;
